luating from right to left ...\n10 * (1) = 10\n10 * (10) = 100\n10 * (100) = 1000","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: functions = [], x = 42\nOutput: 42\nExplanation:\nThe composition of zero functions is the identity function","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `-1000 <= x <= 1000`\n\n- `0 <= functions.length <= 1000`\n\n- all functions accept and return a single integer","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["JavaScript"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Easy","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Given an array of functions `[f1, f2, f3, ..., fn]`, return a new function `fn` that is the **function composition** of the array of functions.\n\nThe **function composition** of `[f(x), g(x), h(x)]` is `fn(x) = f(g(h(x)))`.\n\nThe **function composition** of an empty list of functions is the **identity function** `f(x) = x`.\n\nYou may assume each function in the array accepts one integer as input and returns one integer as output.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: functions = [x => x + 1, x => x * x, x => 2 * x], x = 4\nOutput: 65\nExplanation:\nEvaluating from right to left ...\nStarting with x = 4.\n2 * (4) = 8\n(8) * (8) = 64\n(64) + 1 = 65\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: functions = [x => 10 * x, x => 10 * x, x => 10 * x], x = 1\nOutput: 1000\nExplanation:\nEvaluating from right to left ...\n10 * (1) = 10\n10 * (10) = 100\n10 * (100) = 1000\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: functions = [], x = 42\nOutput: 42\nExplanation:\nThe composition of zero functions is the identity function\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `-1000 <= x <= 1000`\n\n- `0 <= functions.length <= 1000`\n\n- all functions accept and return a single integer","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/function-composition/","problemName":"Function Composition","problemNumber":2629,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Given an array of functions `[f1, f2, f3, ..., fn]`, return a new function `fn` that is the **function composition** of the array of functions.\n\nThe **function composition** of `[f(x), g(x), h(x)]` is `fn(x) = f(g(h(x)))`.\n\nThe **function composition** of an empty list of functions is the **identity function** `f(x) = x`.\n\nYou may assume each function in the array accepts one integer as input and returns one integer as output.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: functions = [x => x + 1, x => x * x, x => 2 * x], x = 4\nOutput: 65\nExplanation:\nEvaluating from right to left ...\nStarting with x = 4.\n2 * (4) = 8\n(8) * (8) = 64\n(64) + 1 = 65","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: functions = [x => 10 * x, x => 10 * x, x => 10 * x], x = 1\nOutput: 1000\nExplanation:\nEvaluating from right to left ...\n10 * (1) = 10\n10 * (10) = 100\n10 * (100) = 1000","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: functions = [], x = 42\nOutput: 42\nExplanation:\nThe composition of zero functions is the identity function","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `-1000 <= x <= 1000`\n\n- `0 <= functions.length <= 1000`\n\n- all functions accept and return a single integer","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Easy","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"Given an array of functions `[f1, f2, f3, ..., fn]`, return a new function `fn` that is the **function composition** of the array of functions.\n\nThe **function composition** of `[f(x), g(x), h(x)]` is `fn(x) = f(g(h(x)))`.\n\nThe **function composition** of an empty list of functions is the **identity function** `f(x) = x`.\n\nYou may assume each function in the array accepts one integer as input and returns one integer as output.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: functions = [x => x + 1, x => x * x, x => 2 * x], x = 4\nOutput: 65\nExplanation:\nEvaluating from right to left ...\nStarting with x = 4.\n2 * (4) = 8\n(8) * (8) = 64\n(64) + 1 = 65\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: functions = [x => 10 * x, x => 10 * x, x => 10 * x], x = 1\nOutput: 1000\nExplanation:\nEvaluating from right to left ...\n10 * (1) = 10\n10 * (10) = 100\n10 * (100) = 1000\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: functions = [], x = 42\nOutput: 42\nExplanation:\nThe composition of zero functions is the identity function\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `-1000 <= x <= 1000`\n\n- `0 <= functions.length <= 1000`\n\n- all functions accept and return a single integer","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/function-composition/","problemName":"Function Composition","problemNumber":2629,"problemSlug":"function-composition","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2629,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["JavaScript"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Given a function `fn`, return a **memoized** version of that function.\n\nA **memoized **function is a function that will never be called twice with the same inputs. Instead it will return a cached value.\n\n`fn` can be any function and there are no constraints on what type of values it accepts. Inputs are considered identical if they are `===` to each other.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: \ngetInputs = () => [[2,2],[2,2],[1,2]]\nfn = function (a, b) { return a + b; }\nOutput: [{\"val\":4,\"calls\":1},{\"val\":4,\"calls\":1},{\"val\":3,\"calls\":2}]\nExplanation:\nconst inputs = getInputs();\nconst memoized = memoize(fn);\nfor (const arr of inputs) {\n  memoized(...arr);\n}\n\nFor the inputs of (2, 2): 2 + 2 = 4, and it required a call to fn().\nFor the inputs of (2, 2): 2 + 2 = 4, but those inputs were seen before so no call to fn() was required.\nFor the inputs of (1, 2): 1 + 2 = 3, and it required another call to fn() for a total of 2.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: \ngetInputs = () => [[{},{}],[{},{}],[{},{}]] \nfn = function (a, b) { return ({...a, ...b}); }\nOutput: [{\"val\":{},\"calls\":1},{\"val\":{},\"calls\":2},{\"val\":{},\"calls\":3}]\nExplanation:\nMerging two empty objects will always result in an empty object. It may seem like there should only be 1 call to fn() because of cache-hits, however none of those objects are === to each other.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: \ngetInputs = () => { const o = {}; return [[o,o],[o,o],[o,o]]; }\nfn = function (a, b) { return ({...a, ...b}); }\nOutput: [{\"val\":{},\"calls\":1},{\"val\":{},\"calls\":1},{\"val\":{},\"calls\":1}]\nExplanation:\nMerging two empty objects will always result in an empty object. The 2nd and 3rd third function calls result in a cache-hit. This is because every object passed in is identical.","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= inputs.length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `0 <= inputs.flat().length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `inputs[i][j] != NaN`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["JavaScript"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Hard","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Given a function `fn`, return a **memoized** version of that function.\n\nA **memoized **function is a function that will never be called twice with the same inputs. Instead it will return a cached value.\n\n`fn` can be any function and there are no constraints on what type of values it accepts. Inputs are considered identical if they are `===` to each other.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: \ngetInputs = () => [[2,2],[2,2],[1,2]]\nfn = function (a, b) { return a + b; }\nOutput: [{\"val\":4,\"calls\":1},{\"val\":4,\"calls\":1},{\"val\":3,\"calls\":2}]\nExplanation:\nconst inputs = getInputs();\nconst memoized = memoize(fn);\nfor (const arr of inputs) {\n  memoized(...arr);\n}\n\nFor the inputs of (2, 2): 2 + 2 = 4, and it required a call to fn().\nFor the inputs of (2, 2): 2 + 2 = 4, but those inputs were seen before so no call to fn() was required.\nFor the inputs of (1, 2): 1 + 2 = 3, and it required another call to fn() for a total of 2.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: \ngetInputs = () => [[{},{}],[{},{}],[{},{}]] \nfn = function (a, b) { return ({...a, ...b}); }\nOutput: [{\"val\":{},\"calls\":1},{\"val\":{},\"calls\":2},{\"val\":{},\"calls\":3}]\nExplanation:\nMerging two empty objects will always result in an empty object. It may seem like there should only be 1 call to fn() because of cache-hits, however none of those objects are === to each other.\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: \ngetInputs = () => { const o = {}; return [[o,o],[o,o],[o,o]]; }\nfn = function (a, b) { return ({...a, ...b}); }\nOutput: [{\"val\":{},\"calls\":1},{\"val\":{},\"calls\":1},{\"val\":{},\"calls\":1}]\nExplanation:\nMerging two empty objects will always result in an empty object. The 2nd and 3rd third function calls result in a cache-hit. This is because every object passed in is identical.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= inputs.length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `0 <= inputs.flat().length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `inputs[i][j] != NaN`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/memoize-ii/","problemName":"Memoize II","problemNumber":2630,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Given a function `fn`, return a **memoized** version of that function.\n\nA **memoized **function is a function that will never be called twice with the same inputs. Instead it will return a cached value.\n\n`fn` can be any function and there are no constraints on what type of values it accepts. Inputs are considered identical if they are `===` to each other.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: \ngetInputs = () => [[2,2],[2,2],[1,2]]\nfn = function (a, b) { return a + b; }\nOutput: [{\"val\":4,\"calls\":1},{\"val\":4,\"calls\":1},{\"val\":3,\"cal