\n\nInput: nums = [2,6,1,5]\nOutput: [[2,6],[1,5]]\nExplanation: The initial list has 4 nodes so the first half would be the first 2 elements since ceil(4 / 2) = 2 and the rest which is 2 nodes are in the second half.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- The number of nodes in `list` is in the range `[2, 10⁵]`\n\n- `0 <= Node.val <= 10⁹`\n\n- `LastNode.next = FirstNode` where `LastNode` is the last node of the list and `FirstNode` is the first one","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/split-a-circular-linked-list/","problemName":"Split a Circular Linked List","problemNumber":2674,"problemSlug":"split-a-circular-linked-list","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2674,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["JavaScript"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Write a function that converts an array of objects `arr` into a matrix `m`.\n\n`arr` is an array of objects or arrays. Each item in the array can be deeply nested with child arrays and child objects. It can also contain numbers, strings, booleans, and null values.\n\nThe first row `m` should be the column names. If there is no nesting, the column names are the unique keys within the objects. If there is nesting, the column names are the respective paths in the object separated by `\".\"`.\n\nEach of the remaining rows corresponds to an object in `arr`. Each value in the matrix corresponds to a value in an object. If a given object doesn't contain a value for a given column, the cell should contain an empty string `\"\"`.\n\nThe columns in the matrix should be in **lexographically ascending** order.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: \narr = [\n  {\"b\": 1, \"a\": 2},\n  {\"b\": 3, \"a\": 4}\n]\nOutput: \n[\n  [\"a\", \"b\"],\n  [2, 1],\n  [4, 3]\n]\n\nExplanation:\nThere are two unique column names in the two objects: \"a\" and \"b\".\n\"a\" corresponds with [2, 4].\n\"b\" coresponds with [1, 3].","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: \narr = [\n  {\"a\": 1, \"b\": 2},\n  {\"c\": 3, \"d\": 4},\n  {}\n]\nOutput: \n[\n  [\"a\", \"b\", \"c\", \"d\"],\n  [1, 2, \"\", \"\"],\n  [\"\", \"\", 3, 4],\n  [\"\", \"\", \"\", \"\"]\n]\n\nExplanation:\nThere are 4 unique column names: \"a\", \"b\", \"c\", \"d\".\nThe first object has values associated with \"a\" and \"b\".\nThe second object has values associated with \"c\" and \"d\".\nThe third object has no keys, so it is just a row of empty strings.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: \narr = [\n  {\"a\": {\"b\": 1, \"c\": 2}},\n  {\"a\": {\"b\": 3, \"d\": 4}}\n]\nOutput: \n[\n  [\"a.b\", \"a.c\", \"a.d\"],\n  [1, 2, \"\"],\n  [3, \"\", 4]\n]\n\nExplanation:\nIn this example, the objects are nested. The keys represent the full path to each value separated by periods.\nThere are three paths: \"a.b\", \"a.c\", \"a.d\".","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Example 4:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":7,"text":"Input: \narr = [\n  [{\"a\": null}],\n  [{\"b\": true}],\n  [{\"c\": \"x\"}]\n]\nOutput: \n[\n  [\"0.a\", \"0.b\", \"0.c\"],\n  [null, \"\", \"\"],\n  [\"\", true, \"\"],\n  [\"\", \"\", \"x\"]\n]\n\nExplanation:\nArrays are also considered objects with their keys being their indices.\nEach array has one element so the keys are \"0.a\", \"0.b\", and \"0.c\".","type":"code"},{"sequence":8,"text":"**Example 5:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":9,"text":"Input: \narr = [\n  {},\n  {},\n  {},\n]\nOutput: \n[\n  [],\n  [],\n  [],\n  []\n]\n\nExplanation:\nThere are no keys so every row is an empty array.","type":"code"},{"sequence":10,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `arr` is a valid JSON array\n\n- `1 <= arr.length <= 1000`\n\n- `unique keys <= 1000`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["JavaScript"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Hard","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Write a function that converts an array of objects `arr` in