finiteObject();\nobj['abc123'](); // \"abc123\"\nThe returned string should always match the method name.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: method = \".-qw73n|^2It\"\nOutput: \".-qw73n|^2It\"\nExplanation: The returned string should always match the method name.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `0 <= method.length <= 1000`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["JavaScript"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Easy","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Write a function that returns an **infinite-method**** object**.\n\nAn **infinite-method**** object** is defined as an object that allows you to call any method and it will always return the name of the method.\n\nFor example, if you execute `obj.abc123()`, it will return `\"abc123\"`.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: method = \"abc123\"\nOutput: \"abc123\"\nExplanation:\nconst obj = createInfiniteObject();\nobj['abc123'](); // \"abc123\"\nThe returned string should always match the method name.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: method = \".-qw73n|^2It\"\nOutput: \".-qw73n|^2It\"\nExplanation: The returned string should always match the method name.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `0 <= method.length <= 1000`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/infinite-method-object/","problemName":"Infinite Method Object","problemNumber":2690,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Write a function that returns an **infinite-method**** object**.\n\nAn **infinite-method**** object** is defined as an object that allows you to call any method and it will always return the name of the method.\n\nFor example, if you execute `obj.abc123()`, it will return `\"abc123\"`.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: method = \"abc123\"\nOutput: \"abc123\"\nExplanation:\nconst obj = createInfiniteObject();\nobj['abc123'](); // \"abc123\"\nThe returned string should always match the method name.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: method = \".-qw73n|^2It\"\nOutput: \".-qw73n|^2It\"\nExplanation: The returned string should always match the method name.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `0 <= method.length <= 1000`","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Easy","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"Write a function that returns an **infinite-method**** object**.\n\nAn **infinite-method**** object** is defined as an object that allows you to call any method and it will always return the name of the method.\n\nFor example, if you execute `obj.abc123()`, it will return `\"abc123\"`.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: method = \"abc123\"\nOutput: \"abc123\"\nExplanation:\nconst obj = createInfiniteObject();\nobj['abc123'](); // \"abc123\"\nThe returned string should always match the method name.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: method = \".-qw73n|^2It\"\nOutput: \".-qw73n|^2It\"\nExplanation: The returned string should always match the method name.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `0 <= method.length <= 1000`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/infinite-method-object/","problemName":"Infinite Method Object","problemNumber":2690,"problemSlug":"infinite-method-object","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2690,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["JavaScript"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Creating clones of immutable objects with minor alterations can be a tedious process. Write a class `ImmutableHelper` that serves as a tool to help with this requirement. The constructor accepts an immutable object `obj` which will be a JSON object or array.\n\nThe class has a single method `produce` which accepts a function `mutator`. The function returns a new object which is similar to the original except it has those mutations applied.\n\n`mutator` accepts a **proxied** version of `obj`. A user of this function can (appear to) mutate this object, but the original object `obj` should not actually be effected.\n\nFor example, a user could write code like this:","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"const originalObj = {\"x\": 5};\nconst helper = new ImmutableHelper(originalObj);\nconst newObj = helper.produce((proxy) => {\n  proxy.x = proxy.x + 1;\n});\nconsole.log(originalObj); // {\"x\": 5}\nconsole.log(newObj); // {\"x\": 6}","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"Properties of the `mutator` function:\n\n- It will always return `undefined`.\n\n- It will never access keys that don't exist.\n\n- It will never delete keys (`delete obj.key`)\n\n- It will never call methods on a proxied object (`push`, `shift`, etc).\n\n- It will never set keys to objects (`proxy.x = {}`)\n\n**Note on how the solution will be tested:** the solution validator will only analyze differences between what was returned and the original `obj`. Doing a full comparison would be too computationally expensive. Also, any mutations to the original object will result in a wrong answer.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: \nobj = {\"val\": 10}, \nmutators = [\n  proxy => { proxy.val += 1; },\n  proxy => { proxy.val -= 1; }\n]\nOutput: \n[\n  {\"val\": 11},\n  {\"val\": 9}\n]\nExplanation:\nconst helper = new ImmutableHelper({val: 10});\nhelper.produce(proxy => { proxy.val += 1; }); // { \"val\": 11 }\nhelper.produce(proxy => { proxy.val -= 1; }); // { \"val\": 9 }","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: \nobj = {\"arr\": [1, 2, 3]} \nmutators = [\n proxy => { \n   proxy.arr[0] = 5; \n   proxy.newVal = proxy.arr[0] + proxy.arr[1];\n }\n]\nOutput: \n[\n  {\"arr\": [5, 2, 3], \"newVal\": 7 } \n]\nExplanation: Two edits were made to the original array. The first element in the array was to set 5. Then a new key was added with a value of 7.","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":7,"text":"Input: \nobj = {\"obj\": {\"val\": {\"x\": 10, \"y\": 20}}}\nmutators = [\n  proxy => { \n    let data = proxy.obj.val; \n    let temp = data.x; \n    data.x = data.y; \n    data.y = temp; \n  }\n]\nOutput: \n[\n  {\"obj\": {\"val\": {\"x\": 20, \"y\": 10}}}\n]\nExplanation: The values of \"x\" and \"y\" were swapped.","type":"code"},{"sequence":8,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `2 <= JSON.stringify(obj).length <= 4 * 10⁵`\n\n- `mutators` is an array of functions\n\n- `total calls to produce() < 10⁵`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["JavaScript"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Hard","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Creating clones of immutable objects with minor alterations can be a tedious process. Write a class `ImmutableHelper` that serves as a tool to help with this requirement. The constructor accepts an immutable object `obj` which will be a JSON object or array.\n\nThe class has a single method `produce` which accepts a function `mutator`. The function returns a new object which is similar to the original except it has those mutations applied.\n\n`mutator` accepts a **proxied** version of `obj`. A user of this function can (appear to) mutate this object, but the original object `obj` should not actually be effected.\n\nFor example, a user could write code like this:\n\nconst originalObj = {\"x\": 5};\nconst helper = new ImmutableHelper(originalObj);\nconst newObj = helper.produce((proxy) => {\n  proxy.x = proxy.x + 1;\n});\nconsole.log(originalObj); // {\"x\": 5}\nconsole.log(newObj); // {\"x\": 6}\n\nProperties of the `mutator` function:\n\n- It will always return `undefined`.\n\n- It will never access keys that don't exist.\n\n- It will never delete keys (`delete obj.key`)\n\n- It will never call methods on a proxied object (`push`, `shift`, etc).\n\n- It will never set keys to objects (`proxy.x = {}`)\n\n**Note on how the solution will be tested:** the solution validator will only analyze differences between what was returned and the original `obj`. Doing a full comparison would be too computationally expensive. Also, any mutations to the original object will result in a wrong answer.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: \nobj = {\"val\": 10}, \nmutators = [\n  proxy => { proxy.val += 1; },\n  proxy => { proxy.val -= 1; }\n]\nOutput: \n[\n  {\"val\": 11},\n  {\"val\": 9}\n]\nExplanation:\nconst helper = new ImmutableHelper({val: 10});\nhelper.produce(proxy => { proxy.val += 1; }); // { \"val\": 11 }\nhelper.produce(proxy => { proxy.val -= 1; }); // { \"val\": 9 }\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: \nobj = {\"arr\": [1, 2, 3]} \nmutators = [\n proxy => { \n   proxy.arr[0] = 5; \n   proxy.newVal = proxy.arr[0] + proxy.arr[1];\n }\n]\nOutput: \n[\n  {\"arr\": [5, 2, 3], \"newVal\": 7 } \n]\nExplanation: Two edits were made to the original array. The first element in the array was to set 5. Then a new key was added with a value of 7.\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: \nobj = {\"obj\": {\"val\": {\"x\": 10, \"y\": 20}}}\nmutators = [\n  proxy => { \n    let data = proxy.obj.val; \n    let temp = data.x; \n    data.x = data.y; \n    data.y = temp; \n  }\n]\nOutput: \n[\n  {\"obj\": {\"val\": {\"x\": 20, \"y\": 10}}}\n]\nExplanation: The values of \"x\" and \"y\" were swapped.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `2 <= JSON.stringify(obj).length <= 4 * 10⁵`\n\n- `mutators` is an array of functions\n\n- `total calls to produce() < 10⁵`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/immutability-helper/","problemName":"Immutability Helper","problemNumber":2691,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Creating clones of immutable objects with minor alterations can be a tedious process. Write a class `ImmutableHelper` that serves as a tool to help with this requirement. The constructor accepts an 